<article>
    <h1>Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore Dis&#xAD;cov&#xAD;ery Cen&#xAD;tre</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WHERE 510 Up­per Jurong Road AD­MIS­SION The Per­ma­nent Ex­hibits Gallery is free for Sin­ga­pore­ans and per­ma­nent res­i­dents. The Black Lake Fa­cil­ity es­cape room tick­ets cost up­wards of $24 for chil­dren be­tween three and 12 years old, and $30 for adults. The Black Lake Laser Bat­tle­field tick­ets are $12 each for chil­dren aged seven to 12, and $15 for those aged 13 and above</p>
    <p>INFO www.sdc.com.sg</p>
    <p>THE LOW­DOWN</p>
    <p>The cen­tre re­cently re­opened af­ter a six-month renovation.</p>
    <p>Its new of­fer­ings in­clude a re­vamped ex­hibits gallery, Through The Lens Of Time; es­cape rooms; and a laser tag arena.</p>
    <p>With 13 rooms, the Black Lake Fa­cil­ity is the largest multi-storey es­cape room at­trac­tion in Sin­ga­pore. The Black Lake Laser Bat­tle­field laser tag room is said to be the first here to fea­ture in­ter­ac­tive pro­jec­tions on its walls.</p>
    <p>FUN FAC­TOR</p>
    <p>Work­ing out the puz­zles in the science-fic­tion-themed es­cape rooms takes team­work and turns out to be a fun fam­ily bond­ing ex­er­cise. At the laser tag arena (above), my seven-year-old has a blast run­ning around shoot­ing her op­po­nents – a notch above the phone- and tablet-based games she is used to play­ing.</p>
    <p>LEARN­ING VALUE</p>
    <p>Through The Lens Of Time is es­sen­tially one big Sin­ga­pore his­tory les­son that in­cor­po­rates aug­mented re­al­ity (AR), multi-screen cin­ema and In­sta­gram-wor­thy in­stal­la­tions. Th­ese in­clude war-torn build­ings from World War II and a life-size replica of the ca­ble car (above) that trag­i­cally fell into the sea in 1983.</p>
    <p>A high­light for my el­der daugh­ter is pre­tend­ing to be a news­caster in a mock stu­dio, read­ing aloud news from piv­otal mo­ments in Sin­ga­pore’s his­tory.</p>
    <p>In de­ci­pher­ing the es­cape room puz­zles, she is in­ad­ver­tently in­tro­duced to maths, science and ge­og­ra­phy con­cepts. Two thumbs up from the par­ents.</p>
    <p>ROOM FOR IM­PROVE­MENT</p>
    <p>The lo­ca­tion. Sin­ga­pore Dis­cov­ery Cen­tre lies in the far­ther reaches of Jurong. There is noth­ing much else to see around the area, save for army camps and in­dus­trial ar­eas, if you are hop­ing to make a day trip of it.</p>
    <p>INSIDER TIP</p>
    <p>Make time for a lake­side din­ing ex­pe­ri­ence at the al­fresco area of the cen­tre’s The Wild Thyme Cafe. It serves fun kids’ meal op­tions.</p>
    <p>Also, down­load the mySDC app be­fore­hand. There are plenty of ad­di­tional au­dio-vis­ual and AR fea­tures to un­lock at var­i­ous ex­hibits.</p>
    <p>WILL WE BE BACK?</p>
    <p>Maybe. But we will wait for the new ex­hi­bi­tion area, set to open next year, to be ready.</p>

